@node "EnglishDoc" "EnglishDoc"

    ENGLISH DOCUMENTATION


        This @{"MYGY" link "EnglishMYGY" 0}-based little utility has especially been  made  for
file-manager  tools  like  "Directory  Opus" or "DiskMaster". InfoMod  gives
you some important informations about sound modules.  I've made this utility
because  DOpus  doesn't  have  any  feature  for  music modules informations
like  FileMaster  has.  For example to see from whom the module has been
composed, the only way was to HEX-READ your module file.


    @{"Features" link "EnglishFeatures" 0}
    @{"Requirements" link "EnglishRequirements" 0}
    @{"UsageĀwithĀCLI" link "EnglishUsage" 0}
    @{"InstallationĀprocedureĀforĀDOpus" link "EnglishInstallDOpus" 0}
    @{"History" link "EnglishHistory" 0}
@endnode

@node "EnglishMYGY" "EnglishMYGY"
@prev "EnglishDoc"

    MYGY is the Acronym of 'Make Your GUI Yourself' ! (« Revolution)
    It does mean that this is a pure util to insert with an external
    GUI like DirectoryOpus for example and use the best OS available,
    The AmigaOS !

    For non informed people GUI is the generic name of "Graphical User
    Interface". Your Workbench is one of the first usable GUI available
    on the computer story.
@endnode

@node "EnglishFeatures" "Features"

    - Recognize a lot of sound module formats:
         - Protracker, Startrekker     - Fred Modules
         - Scream Tracker III (S3M)    - JamCracker Modules
         - PlaySid Onefile Modules     - Future Composer (1.3 and 1.4)
         - SoundMonitor Modules        - COSO Modules (Hippel & Atari)
         - MED modules                 - Startrekker Modules
	 - Sonic Arranger 1 & 2        - Old soundtracker Modules
         - Take & Fast Tracker modules - FTM
	 - Fred Modules		       - Oktalizer
	 - Extended FastTracker II     - TMFX
         - Sidmon V1.0                 - VectorDean
         - Delta Music 1 & 2           - David Wittaker
         - Ron Klaren                  - Digital Mugician
         - Custom                      - Art of Noise (4 & 8 Channels)
         - AProSys                     - AY ZX Spectrum
         - DSS                         - Hippel
         - Hippel 7 Channels           - In Stereo (INS)
         - Leggless Music Editor       - Mark II
         - Music Line Editor           - Music Assembler
         - Mark Cooksey                - MON
         - Martin Walker               - SidMon II
         - Sound FX V1.0               - StoneTracker
         - Synthesis                   - Symphonie

    - Display a lot of Protracker informations in one screen :
         - Real name                   - Number of positions used
         - The 31 samples names        - Number of patterns
         - KB lenght of the patterns   - Number of instruments used
         - KB lenght of the samples

    - Search fastly into chip-ram for a protracker module

    - Unpack Powerpacked & XPKed modules

    - It's free... If you would send money send it to some caritative
      associations like greenpeace etc...

@endnode

@node "EnglishRequirements" "Requirements"

    - AmigaOS    :-)    From 1.2 to 3.1
    - XPKmaster.library
    - PowerPacker.library
@endnode

@node "EnglishInstallDOpus" "Installation with DOpus"
 BEST WAY TO INSTALL IT WITH DIRECTORY OPUS :
 --------------------------------------------

        1) Be sure you've xpkmaster.library, powerpacker.library and some
           compressors libs into your LIBS: directory.
        2) Copy InfoMod in the C: directory
        3) Select 'CONFIGURE' in the first menu of DOpus
        4) Select 'BUTTON', and add a button with INFOMOD name
        5) As 'new entry' enter AmigaDOS c:InfoMod -M {f}
        6) Enter zero (0) as 'close delay'
        7) Select the flag 'Output window'
        8) Click 'Okay' 'Okay' 'Save'
        9) I suggest you to enter as 'System' and 'AmigaDOS' this
           window parameters :
           CON:0/11/639/175/Directory...
@endnode

@node "EnglishUsage" "Usage of Infomod"
        Usage :  InfoMod [<module name>] [-M]

        If you type infomod without anything, it will search the first
protracker module that can be found in the CHIP-Memory... I hope that this
one is the module who is actualy played with ANY players you want or with
the internal player from DOpus. Note that this doesn't work with Hippoplayer
because it change the protracker instruments name directly when the module
is loaded. So the information in chip ram is not readable and if then I didn't
display such module.

        If you type infomod with a name of module it will display the
informations concerning this module. It can read simple protracker modules
(or startrecker modules) and since 1.4 a lot of other module formats (see
@{"Features" link "EnglishFeatures" 0}).

        If  the  file  you  want  to  have informations about is a
PowerPacked modules   or   a   XPK   modules   thanx  to  the
xpkmaster.library  and  the powerpacker.library it will decrunch it and give
you the informations.

        As  parameter  you  can  indicate  the  '-M'  if you want that
Infomod generate a LeftMouseWait before exit.
@endnode

@node "EnglishHistory" "History from InfoMod"
V1.0    (Internal)      -Just display informations.

V1.1    (april 94)      -Added xpkmaster.library ressources.
                        -Added command '-M' for waiting leftmouse.
                        -Only read needed top bytes for requested
                         informations.

V1.2    (may 94)        -Fast algorithm to find protracker mod in
                         CHIP memory.

V1.3    (1 june 94)     -Fixed bug that crashes InfoMod with KS1.3
                        -Better testing purpose before displaying a
                         protracker mod found in memory

V1.4    (1 april 95!)   -One year of coding holidays...
        (4312 bytes)    -Recognize a lot of other sound modules format
                        -Improved Documentation in AmigaGuide Format

V1.5    (21 april 95)   -Knows a lot more format (see features)
        (5512 bytes)

V1.6    (17 july 95)    -Knows some more format (see features)
        (5648 bytes)    -Documentation is upgraded

V1.7    (31 dec 95)     -Knows 6 new formats (see features)
        (6536 bytes)    -Now display 'Comment files' if available
                        -Fixed big dos-lock files bug (you can't
                         delete a mod after viewing and XPK packed
                         module with older versions)
                        -Didn't display corrupted Hippoplayer modules
                         when searching in chip-ram.
V1.8    (08 july 96)    -Knows 18 new modules format thanks to
        (9432 bytes)     the quadruple CD from Gryzor (!!)
                        -fixed bug when displaying S3M or XM mods.
                        -Some more information for some formats and
                         a better detection of some of them.
                        -First release for Aminet

@endnode

@node "FrenchDoc" "documentation en francais"

    DOCUMENTATION EN FRANCAIS

        Ce petit utilitaire basķ sur le concept du @{"MYGY" link "FrenchMYGY" 0} a ķtķ spķcialement
crķe pour les utilitaires de gestion de fichier tel "Directory Opus" ou
"DiskMaster". Infomod vous permet d'avoir des informations utiles sur un tas
de format diffķrents de modules de musiques. J'ai fait cet utilitaire
principalement parce que DOpus ne permet pas de visualiser les instruments
d'un modules comme le permettait FileMaster que j'utilisait avant. Le seul
recours que j'avais etait de faire une visualisation en HEXadķcimal pour
lire les instruments de mes modules.


    @{"Descriptif" link "FrenchFeatures" 0}
    @{"CeĀqu'ilĀvousĀfaut" link "FrenchRequirements" 0}
    @{"UtilisationĀsousĀCLI" link "FrenchUsage" 0}
    @{"ProcķdureĀd'installationĀsousĀDOpus" link "FrenchInstallDOpus" 0}
    @{"Historique" link "FrenchHistory" 0}
@endnode

@node "FrenchMYGY" "Explications sur le MYGY"

    MYGY est l'acronyme anglais de 'Make Your GUI Yourself' (« Revolution)
    Cela veut dire que cet utilitaire est Ó inserer Ó un environnement GUI
    externe comme DirectoryOpus et qui utilise le meilleur systÓme
    d'exploiration disponible, l'AmigaOS

    Pour ceux qui ne le savent pas, GUI est le terme gķnķrique de Graphical
    User Interface. Votre Workbench a ķtķ l'un des premier GUI disponible
    dans l'histoire de la micro-informatique.
@endnode

